04479nam a22005175i 9780226059099DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132013ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013007451  a9780226059099  a(DE-B1597)524281  a(OCoLC)859536721  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQH361b.R534 2013 7aSCI0000002bisacsh1 aRichards, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWas Hitler a Darwinian? :bDisputed Questions in the History of Evolutionary Theory /cRobert J. Richards. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b5 color plates, 33 halftones, 7 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Darwin’s Theory of Natural Selection and Its Moral Purpose -- t3. Darwin’s Principle of Divergence: Why Fodor Was Almost Right -- t4. Darwin’s Romantic Quest: Mind, Morals, and Emotions -- t5. The Relation of Spencer’s Evolutionary Theory to Darwin’s -- t6. Ernst Haeckel’s Scientific and Artistic Struggles -- t7. Haeckel’s Embryos: Fraud Not Proven -- t8. The Linguistic Creation of Man: August Schleicher and the Missing Link in Darwinian Theory -- t9. Was Hitler a Darwinian? -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn tracing the history of Darwin’s accomplishment and the trajectory of evolutionary theory during the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, most scholars agree that Darwin introduced blind mechanism into biology, thus banishing moral values from the understanding of nature. According to the standard interpretation, the principle of survival of the fittest has rendered human behavior, including moral behavior, ultimately selfish. Few doubt that Darwinian theory, especially as construed by the master’s German disciple, Ernst Haeckel, inspired Hitler and led to Nazi atrocities. In this collection of essays, Robert J. Richards argues that this orthodox view is wrongheaded. A close historical examination reveals that Darwin, in more traditional fashion, constructed nature with a moral spine and provided it with a goal: man as a moral creature. The book takes up many other topics—including the character of Darwin’s chief principles of natural selection and divergence, his dispute with Alfred Russel Wallace over man’s big brain, the role of language in human development, his relationship to Herbert Spencer, how much his views had in common with Haeckel’s, and the general problem of progress in evolution. Moreover, Richards takes a forceful stand on the timely issue of whether Darwin is to blame for Hitler’s atrocities. Was Hitler a Darwinian? is intellectual history at its boldest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEvolution (Biology)xHistory. 0aHuman evolution - Moral and ethical aspects. 0aHuman evolutionxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aevolution, evolutionary, darwin, darwinian, controversy, controversial, myth, questions, answers, theory, theoretical, dispute, argument, 1800s, 1900s, history, historical, biology, biologist, morals, nature, natural world, analysis, interpretation, species, human, behavior, haeckel, hitler, nazis, essay collection, academic, scholarly, research.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226059099423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226059099/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles